		<header>
			
			<h1>Final stage of EPA negotiations generating tensions between EAC members </h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 March 2014
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the Kenya Flower Council, the Kenyan President has made a commitment “to take charge of the EU-EAC Economic Partnership Agreement (EPA) negotiations” to ensure that the negotiations are completed before the 1 October 2014 deadline. This follows the failure of the January 2014 negotiating session to conclude the negotiations,&nbsp; given outstanding disagreements on “economic and development co-operation, rules of origin, export taxes and the most-favoured nation clause”.&nbsp;</p><p>The Kenya Institute for Public Policy Research and Analysis has argued that Kenyan officials “did not push hard enough for a common position for the region”. The CEO of the Fresh Produce and Exporters Associations of Kenya (FPEAK) and the Kenya Flower Council have called respectively for officials to “push harder” and for negotiators to “spend more time resolving the pending issues”.&nbsp; These calls need to be seen in the context of Latin American exporters actively looking to take over flower markets from Kenyan exporters if the EU does impose import duties on Kenyan flower exports from 1 October 2014.</p><p>East African negotiators, however, have blamed the EC for some of the delays, following the introduction of issues such as “good governance in tax matters”.&nbsp; There are also reportedly concerns in East Africa that as a result of the proposed non-execution clause, “future trade relations… will be based on governance issues as opposed to commercial concerns.”&nbsp; The perceptions that the relevant variables tend to be “loosely defined by the West, depending on the country involved” and that non-execution clauses are “subject to unilateral interpretation and execution” are a particular cause for concern.</p><p>On the MFN clause, EU officials argue that the EU is only seeking a level playing field, and that the EU “would be doing itself a disservice if levies charged on its exports to East African nations are higher compared to those imposed on products from its competitors such as China”. EC officials reportedly sense “a lack of commitment by several EAC nations”, with Tanzania and Burundi being considered “non-committal”. Unlike Kenya, the LDCs in the EAC will continue to enjoy duty-free access to the EU market after 1 October 2014 under the Everything But Arms (EBA) initiative, regardless of the outcome of the EPA negotiations. According to EC officials, “Kenya is in a tricky position, and that is why it has to marshal [its] neighbours into grabbing this window of opportunity.”</p><p>Meanwhile, at the East African meeting of the ACP–EU joint Parliamentary Assembly in Mauritius in February, members adopted a communiqué which emphasised “the crucial importance of regional integration in creating an enabling environment for economic growth, employment, development and poverty reduction” and underlined “the need for EPAs to foster development and to support regional integration”.</p><p>According to the Kenya Flower Council, if current preferences are not extended, “Kenya will not be able to compete on price, and market share will be lost”, since “countries like Colombia, Tanzania, Uganda, Rwanda, Burundi and Ethiopia will continue to enjoy their duty-free status with the EU” (see <i>Agritrade </i>article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/EPAs/Concerns-grow-in-Kenya-as-EAC-EU-EPA-negotiations-continue" target="_blank">Concerns grow in Kenya as EAC–EU EPA negotiations continue</a>’, 6 March 2014).&nbsp; In addition to cut flowers, products potentially affected include “fresh fruit and vegetables, fish and fish products, textiles and apparel, nuts, hides and skins”, where GSP duties of between 8.5 and 15.7% would be charged.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
