				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The EC is looking to the Kenyan government to “marshal” the LDC members of the EAC into the EPA agreement, despite a recognition of the “lack of commitment by several EAC nations” to an EPA agreement. This could potentially generate tensions within the EAC, since not only Latin American but also fellow EAC exporters could gain trade and investment benefits if the EU imposed tariffs on Kenyan exports from 1 October 2014.</p><p>Balancing this consideration is the perceived absence of any additional real benefits for LDCs from signing an EPA agreement, which it is felt could impose new obligations, the consequences of which are unknown.</p><p>This would suggest a need to find a way of addressing LDC concerns over the possible implications of a range of proposed provisions, the precise scope of which will be subject to interpretation (e.g. via a declaration on the interpretation of provisions such as the non-execution clause).</p><p>Similarly, the discussions on the MFN clause need to be seen in the context of US concerns over the new preferences that the EPA will extend to EU companies and which are not made available to US companies. With the US Africa Growth and Opportunity Act (AGOA) coming up for renewal, some US exporters are starting to put pressure on the US administration to do something about the tariff disadvantages arising from the implementation of EPA commitments. This needs to be seen against the background of the launching of discussions over a possible EAC–US trade and investment partnership (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘Launch of EAC–US TIP negotiations potentially complicated by other trade agreements’, forthcoming 2014). This provides a wider context to the request from the EC for EAC endorsement of the draft MFN clauses intended to create “a level playing field” for all major trading nations.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
